{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","language":"python","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.13","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":408}],"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":5,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/farhankhanmarwat/breast-cancer-classification-notebook?scriptVersionId=335712444\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"id":"04835c2c","cell_type":"markdown","source":"#  Classification with Machine Learning using Scikit-Learn\n\n### *Breast Cancer Diagnosis Prediction — Comparing Six Classification Algorithms*\n\n---\n\nCancer diagnosis is one of the clearest real-world cases where a well-built classifier\ncan genuinely support (never replace) clinical decision-making. In this notebook we\nbuild, evaluate, and compare **six classification algorithms** to predict whether a\nbreast mass is **malignant** or **benign** from digitized cell-nuclei measurements.\n\nThe emphasis throughout is on doing this the *right* way: identical preprocessing for\nevery model, one shared evaluation function, and metrics chosen deliberately for a\nmedical classification problem — where a false negative (missing a malignant tumor) is\nfar more costly than a false positive.\n\n## Project Objective\n\nTrain and fairly compare six classifiers on the same preprocessed data, identify the\nbest-performing model using multiple metrics (not just accuracy), and draw practical\nconclusions about which approach is best suited to a diagnostic setting.\n\n##  Problem Statement\n\nGiven a set of measurements computed from a digitized image of a breast mass's cell\nnuclei, predict whether the mass is **malignant (M)** or **benign (B)**. This is a\n**binary classification** problem.\n\n##  What is Classification?\n\nClassification is a supervised learning task where the model learns to assign inputs to\none of a fixed set of **discrete categories** (here: malignant or benign) rather than\npredicting a continuous number.\n\n##  Classification vs. Regression\n\n| | Classification | Regression |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Output** | Discrete class label | Continuous numeric value |\n| **Example** | Malignant vs. Benign | Predicting house price |\n| **Typical metrics** | Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1, ROC-AUC | MAE, RMSE, R² |\n| **Decision boundary** | Yes — separates classes | No — fits a continuous surface |\n\n##  Dataset Description\n\n**Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Dataset** — chosen deliberately for this project:\n\n-  **Beginner-friendly** — clean, well-documented, no exotic preprocessing required\n-  **Well-structured** — 569 samples, 30 numeric features, a single binary target\n-  **Widely used** — a standard benchmark for classification, easy to sanity-check\n  results against\n-  **Real diagnostic relevance** — features are computed from real digitized images\n  of fine needle aspirate (FNA) cell nuclei, making the modeling choices meaningful\n  rather than academic\n\nEach row describes one tumor sample, with 10 real-valued cell-nucleus characteristics\n(radius, texture, perimeter, area, smoothness, compactness, concavity, concave points,\nsymmetry, fractal dimension), each summarized three ways: **mean**, **standard error\n(`_se`)**, and **worst (largest) value** — giving 30 features in total, plus an `id`\ncolumn and the `diagnosis` target.\n\n##  Workflow Overview\n\n1. Import libraries\n2. Load & inspect the dataset\n3. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)\n4. Data cleaning & categorical encoding\n5. Feature engineering & train/test split\n6. Feature scaling\n7. Build one reusable evaluation function\n8. Train **six classification models** under identical conditions\n9. Compare results numerically & visually\n10. Crown the best model \n11. Conclude with insights, business relevance & future improvements\n12. What I Learned\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"3cfc85d4","cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n## 1.  Import Libraries","metadata":{}},{"id":"48526f8d","cell_type":"code","source":"# Core data handling\nimport numpy as np\nimport pandas as pd\n\n# Visualization\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport seaborn as sns\n\n# Preprocessing & pipeline\nfrom sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\nfrom sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, LabelEncoder\n\n# Models\nfrom sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\nfrom sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier\nfrom sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier\nfrom sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\nfrom sklearn.svm import SVC\nfrom sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB\n\n# Evaluation\nfrom sklearn.metrics import (\n    accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score,\n    roc_auc_score, roc_curve, confusion_matrix, classification_report\n)\n\n# Plot styling\nsns.set_style(\"whitegrid\")\nplt.rcParams[\"figure.dpi\"] = 72\nplt.rcParams[\"savefig.dpi\"] = 72\nPALETTE = \"viridis\"\n\nRANDOM_STATE = 42\nnp.random.seed(RANDOM_STATE)\n\nprint(\" Libraries imported successfully.\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-07-16T12:06:41.277509Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-07-16T12:06:41.278325Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-07-16T12:06:41.288449Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-07-16T12:06:41.278278Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-07-16T12:06:41.287568Z"},"trusted":true},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":" Libraries imported successfully.\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":2},{"id":"a4ad33ca","cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n## 2.  Load Dataset\n\nThe dataset is loaded directly from the Kaggle CS